words.meaning: Irrelevant or unrelated to the subject being dealt with.
examples: Please omit any extraneous details from your report.
The professor's lecture was full of extraneous information.

words.meaning: To extend the application of (a method or conclusion, especially one based on statistics) to an unknown situation by assuming that existing trends will continue.
examples: We can extrapolate future trends from the current sales data.
It is difficult to extrapolate from this small sample to the entire population.

words.meaning: The action of extrapolating; the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
examples: The report's conclusions are based on an extrapolation of current trends.
Any prediction about the future of technology is just an extrapolation.

words.meaning: Lacking restraint in spending money or using resources.
examples: She has an extravagant taste in clothes.
The extravagant wedding cost a fortune.

words.meaning: Not part of the essential nature of someone or something; coming or operating from outside.
examples: The extrinsic value of the coin is its monetary worth, while its intrinsic value lies in its historical significance.
He was motivated by extrinsic rewards like money and praise.

words.meaning: Filled with or characterized by a lively energy and excitement.
examples: The exuberant crowd cheered for their team.
She has an exuberant and infectious personality.

words.meaning: To feel or show triumphant elation or jubilation.
examples: The team exulted in their victory.
She exulted at the news of her promotion.

words.meaning: A feeling of triumphant elation or jubilation; rejoicing.
examples: There was a great exultation in the streets after the team won the championship.
She felt a sense of exultation at her success.

words.meaning: To invent or concoct (something), typically with deceitful intent.
examples: He was accused of fabricating evidence.
She fabricated a story to explain her absence.

words.meaning: The face of a building, especially the principal front that looks onto a street or open space; an outward appearance that is maintained to conceal a less pleasant or creditable reality.
examples: The building has a beautiful neoclassical facade.
He maintained a facade of confidence, but he was actually very nervous.

words.meaning: One side of something many-sided, especially of a cut gem.
examples: The diamond had many facets, each catching the light.
We need to consider every facet of the problem.

words.meaning: Treating serious issues with deliberately inappropriate humor; flippant.
examples: He was being facetious when he said he wanted to quit his job and join the circus.
Her facetious comments were not appreciated in the serious meeting.

words.meaning: (Especially of a theory or argument) appearing neat and comprehensive only by ignoring the true complexities of an issue; superficial.
examples: He offered a facile solution to a complex problem.
The book was a facile and simplistic account of a difficult historical period.

words.meaning: To make (an action or process) easy or easier.
examples: The new software will facilitate the sharing of information.
A good teacher can facilitate learning.

words.meaning: A small, organized, dissenting group within a larger one, especially in politics.
examples: The political party was split by internal factions.
A faction of the army was plotting a coup.

words.meaning: Relating or inclined to a state of faction.
examples: The factious group was always causing trouble within the organization.
The country was torn apart by factious disputes.

words.meaning: Artificially created or developed.
examples: The factitious crisis was created by the media.
She had a factitious and insincere smile.

words.meaning: An employee who does all kinds of work.
examples: He was the family factotum, doing everything from cooking to gardening.
The small company needed a factotum who could handle a variety of tasks.

words.meaning: Intensely popular for a short time; relating to a fad.
examples: The new diet is just a faddish trend that won't last.
He was known for his faddish and eccentric sense of style.

words.meaning: A person who is a dependable friend only when times are good.
examples: He discovered she was just a fair-weather friend when he lost his job.
True friends stick by you in tough times, unlike fair-weather friends.

words.meaning: Based on a mistaken belief.
examples: His argument was based on a fallacious premise.
It is fallacious to assume that all stereotypes are true.

words.meaning: A mistaken belief, especially one based on unsound argument.
examples: It is a common fallacy that money brings happiness.
The idea that the earth is flat is a fallacy.

words.meaning: Capable of making mistakes or being erroneous.
examples: All human beings are fallible.
The expert's judgment proved to be fallible.

words.meaning: (Of farmland) plowed and harrowed but left unsown for a period in order to restore its fertility as part of a crop rotation or to avoid surplus production.
examples: The fields lay fallow for a year to recover.
His creative talents had lain fallow for years.

words.meaning: To lose strength or momentum.
examples: Her courage did not falter in the face of danger.
The economy began to falter after the stock market crash.

words.meaning: A person filled with excessive and single-minded zeal, especially for an extreme religious or political cause.
examples: He was a religious fanatic who was intolerant of other beliefs.
She is a fitness fanatic who exercises every day.

words.meaning: Filled with excessive and single-minded zeal.
examples: He had a fanatical devotion to his favorite sports team.
The fanatical supporters of the political party were willing to do anything for their leader.

words.meaning: (Of a person or their thoughts and ideas) overimaginative and unrealistic.
examples: She had a fanciful idea of what it would be like to live in a castle.
The book is a fanciful tale about a talking animal.

words.meaning: To feel a desire or liking for.
examples: Do you fancy a cup of tea?
He fancied himself a great singer.

words.meaning: A comic dramatic work using buffoonery and horseplay and typically including crude characterization and ludicrously improbable situations.
examples: The play was a hilarious farce about a mistaken identity.
The trial was a farce, with the outcome already decided.

words.meaning: Very attentive to and concerned about accuracy and detail.
examples: She is a fastidious cleaner who scrubs every inch of the house.
He was fastidious about his appearance and always well-dressed.

words.meaning: A phrase used to suggest that trouble is about to start.
examples: Now that the secret is out, the fat is in the fire.
When the boss found out about the mistake, the fat was in the fire.

words.meaning: Causing death.
examples: The car crash was fatal, and three people were killed.
He made a fatal mistake that cost him his job.

words.meaning: To understand (a difficult problem or an enigmatic person) after much thought.
examples: I can't fathom why he would do such a thing.
It is difficult to fathom the vastness of the universe.

words.meaning: Silly and pointless.
examples: He made a fatuous comment that made everyone groan.
She had a fatuous grin on her face.

words.meaning: The animals of a particular region, habitat, or geological period.
examples: The book describes the flora and fauna of the Amazon rainforest.
The unique fauna of the island includes several endangered species.

words.meaning: To give a servile display of exaggerated flattery or affection, typically in order to gain favor or advantage.
examples: The courtiers would fawn over the king, hoping to gain his favor.
She disliked people who would fawn over celebrities.

words.meaning: Displaying exaggerated flattery or affection; obsequious.
examples: He had a fawning and sycophantic manner.
The fawning assistant agreed with everything her boss said.

words.meaning: Possible to do easily or conveniently.
examples: It is not feasible to build a new bridge with the current budget.
The plan is feasible and could be implemented quickly.

words.meaning: Lacking initiative or strength of character; irresponsible.
examples: He was a feckless and lazy person who never accomplished anything.
The feckless administration was unable to solve the country's problems.

words.meaning: Producing or capable of producing an abundance of offspring or new growth; fertile.
examples: The fecund soil produced a bountiful harvest.
She was a fecund writer who produced many novels.

words.meaning: Lacking physical strength, especially as a result of age or illness.
examples: He was a feeble old man who could barely walk.
She made a feeble attempt to defend her actions.

words.meaning: Drunk; intoxicated.
examples: After a few beers, he was feeling no pain.
The party guests were feeling no pain by the end of the night.

words.meaning: To pretend to be affected by (a feeling, state, or injury).
examples: He would often feign illness to get out of work.
She feigned surprise, but she already knew the secret.

words.meaning: A deceptive or pretended blow, thrust, or other movement, especially in boxing or fencing.
examples: The boxer made a feint with his left hand and then landed a punch with his right.
Her offer to help was just a feint to get access to the confidential information.

words.meaning: To congratulate.
examples: We felicitate you on your recent success.
The president sent a message to felicitate the new leader.

words.meaning: Well chosen or suited to the circumstances.
examples: He made a felicitous remark that broke the tension in the room.
The book's title is particularly felicitous.

words.meaning: Intense happiness.
examples: She lived a life of great felicity and contentment.
He expressed his feelings with great felicity of language.

words.meaning: Of terrible evil or ferocity; deadly.
examples: The dragon was a fell beast that terrorized the countryside.
He was struck down by a fell disease.

words.meaning: A person who has been convicted of a felony.
examples: The convicted felon was sentenced to ten years in prison.
As a felon, he was not allowed to own a firearm.

words.meaning: (Especially of an animal) in a wild state, especially after escape from captivity or domestication.
examples: A pack of feral dogs roamed the streets.
The feral cat was difficult to tame.

words.meaning: To incite or stir up (trouble or disorder).
examples: The politician's speech was intended to ferment unrest.
The revolutionary ideas began to ferment among the people.

words.meaning: To search tenaciously for and find something.
examples: The reporter was trying to ferret out the truth.
She ferreted through her purse for her keys.

words.meaning: Having or displaying a passionate intensity.
examples: He was a fervent supporter of the cause.
She made a fervent plea for help.

words.meaning: Intensely enthusiastic or passionate, especially to an excessive degree.
examples: He had a fervid imagination.
The fervid crowd cheered for their team.

words.meaning: Intense and passionate feeling.
examples: He spoke with great fervor about his religious beliefs.
The revolutionary fervor swept through the country.

words.meaning: (Of a wound or sore) to become septic; suppurate. (Of a negative feeling or problem) to become worse or more intense, especially through long-term neglect or indifference.
examples: The wound began to fester and needed medical attention.
His resentment was left to fester for years.

words.meaning: To adorn (a place) with ribbons, garlands, or other decorations.
examples: The room was festooned with balloons and streamers for the party.
The ancient temple was festooned with intricate carvings.

words.meaning: To honor or entertain (someone) lavishly.
examples: The victorious team was feted with a parade and a banquet.
The author was feted by her admirers.

words.meaning: Smelling extremely unpleasant.
examples: The fetid smell of rotting garbage filled the air.
The stagnant pond had a fetid odor.
